Professional file organization with clear naming conventions.

Brand Specifications
Brand Colors (with usage guidelines)
Primary Color: Warm Parchment

Hex: #F3F0EC

Usage: 60-70% - Used for all light backgrounds, creating an airy, minimalist, and warm feel.

Secondary Color: Soft Charcoal

Hex: #2A2A2A

Usage: 20-30% - Used for dark-themed sections (like 'Our Story') and primary text on light backgrounds for a softer, more sophisticated feel than pure black.

Accent 1: Antique Gold

Hex: #BA9C7B

Usage: 5-10% - Reserved exclusively for all Call-to-Action (CTA) buttons and key trust icons to guide the user's eye.

Accent 2: Warm Black

Hex: #514F4F

Usage: <5% - Used for primary body text (on light backgrounds) if Soft Charcoal provides insufficient contrast, or for sub-headlines.

Accent 3: Parchment (Text)

Hex: #F3F0EC

Usage: Variable - Used for all text on Soft Charcoal backgrounds to maintain perfect brand consistency.

Typography Hierarchy
Headlines (H1): Playfair Display Regular

Usage: Strong, elegant, high-contrast serif for all main section headlines. Evokes luxury and sophistication.

Font source: Google Fonts

Subheadings (H2): Playfair Display Regular

Usage: Continues the elegant serif style for secondary headlines.

Body Text (H3/Paragraphs): Montserrat Regular

Usage: Clean, minimalist, geometric sans-serif for all body copy. Highly readable and professional.

Call to Action (Buttons): Montserrat Semibold

Usage: All-caps, slightly letter-spaced for action-oriented emphasis on all buttons and icon labels.

Typography Principles:

Maintain generous white space and line height for an airy, uncrowded, and luxurious reading experience.

The high-contrast pairing of Playfair (elegant) and Montserrat (modern) is the core of the brand identity.

Hierarchy is critical: headlines are for emotion, body text is for clarity.

Visual Design Direction
Imagery Approach:

Professional, high-end interior and architectural photography.

Must evoke a "Japandi" or "modern Scandinavian luxury" feel: minimalist, bright, airy, and warm.

Heavy use of natural light, soft shadows, and textures (wood, linen, stone).

What to emphasize: Peace, order, cleanliness, sophistication.

What to avoid: Clutter, dark/moody photos, generic stock photos, people. The space is the hero.

Photography Guidelines: Use:

Well-lit, minimalist living rooms.

Serene, spa-like bedrooms or bathrooms.

Close-ups of quality materials (e.g., wood grain, marble).

Architectural details with clean lines.

Avoid:

"Busy" or "lived-in" messes.

Overly-saturated, HDR, or unrealistic images.

People, unless they are abstract and out of focus.

Design Principles:

Generous white space is non-negotiable; it is the primary design element.

A strong, clean grid layout.

A calm, story-driven flow that feels like a luxury magazine.

Ideal Customer Avatar
Who is your perfect client? A high-net-worth individual, investor, or family office that owns one or more luxury properties. They are time-poor and value-driven (value of peace, not just cost-saving). They are likely frustrated with their current "standard" property manager who is opaque, hard to reach, and provides commodity-level service.

Primary Pain Point: The stress and opacity of property management. Feeling that they have to "manage their manager" and being burdened by constant, "non-luxury" problems. The fear that their valuable asset is being neglected.

Desired Outcome: True, "white-glove" peace of mind. The ability to enjoy their asset, not just administer it. They want a partner who will protect and enhance their property's value with meticulous, proactive care.

Decision Factors: Trust, transparency, level of service, professionalism, and exclusivity.

Emotional Drivers: Desire for peace, security, and freedom from stress.

Logical Justifications: Asset protection, proactive maintenance, and clear, transparent financial reporting.

